            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembered standing on the tarmac at JFK, the New York air biting and unfamiliar, clutching his mother's hand. The sheer scale of the airport, the rush of a language he barely understood \u2013 pure overwhelm. It solidified his determination to adapt, to master this new world his parents had brought him to. He was 16.\n\n2. The email confirming his full scholarship to the Bioinformatics program flashed on the screen; a wave of profound relief washed over him. It felt like the weight of expectation from his family, and his own fierce drive, lifted. He knew then this was his path, a validation of years spent alone in the library. He was 22.\n\n3. The silence of his San Francisco apartment after hanging up with his mother, the news of his father's passing still raw in his ears. A hollow ache settled in his chest. It was the moment his focus shifted, irreversibly, from purely career ascension to a yearning for human connection, for shared moments beyond data analysis. He was 44.\n\n4. Walking through Golden Gate Park on a rare, clear day, the sunlight slanting through the eucalyptus trees, a sense of unexpected peace washed over him. It was a quiet affirmation that stability had a beauty of its own, that the predictable rhythms of his San Francisco life held a certain grace. He was 47.\n\n5. The first time a junior scientist, wide-eyed and earnest, asked for his advice, truly listening to his insights. A warmth spread through him, a quiet pride in knowing his painstakingly accumulated knowledge held value for another. It was a glimpse of a future beyond just his own research, a sense of future purpose. He was 48."
